AGI - He had received an e-mail, apparently sent by judicial or police authorities, with whom he had been informed of the existence of a criminal proceeding charged to criminal offences >online followed an intimation to pay a sum of money under "multa" to close the criminal proceedings before the establishment of the actual trial. This is the case that gave rise to the operation "Polo Est", conducted by the Cyber Security Centre for Lombardy and coordinated by the Bergamo Procura.
&nbsp;
Vittima an Italian citizen residing in China who, considering authentic an email with the logo of the Postal Police and the signature of a police officer (currently retired, but quoted in several websites), has ceded to blackmail paying the total sum of 117.500 euros>. Worried about the effects that such an infamous accusation would have on its reputation, the victim paid a first "multa" of 7,800 euros. After a very short time, he received from the blackmailer additional e-mails containing fake judicial acts that underwent the payment of further sanctions as a result of decisions taken by a fanatical "Corte d'Appello". After months of threats and harassment, accounted for deception, he filed a complaint to the Postal Police of Milan, which reconstructed the movements of money between victim and extortors, as well as, in parallel, between these and the network of "money mule" > to which he was entrusted the task of recycle illicit proceeds. They then identified in Bergamo the premises in which the surveyed lived and operated.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The 12 searches for as many people (an Italian citizen, a Senegalese and ten Nigerians, aged between 25 and 54) have allowed a copious documentation concerning the movement of money from the victim, as well as those relating to the recycling of illicit proceeds. The State Police maintains that in no case official communications and notifications of judicial or administrative acts (as, in fact, pecuniary sanctions) are carried out using e-mail, or at least by telephone communications, even though they come from telephone numbers corresponding to the real ones. In fact, criminals use spoofing techniques to change the sender's e-mail address as well as the calling phone number. Any e-mails bearing heraldic logos of the State Police and/or its specialist departments, alone or associated with those of other authorities, are to be considered absolutely false.
